## ABSTRACT

The Nancy Grace Roman Space Telescope's Galactic Bulge Time-Domain Survey (GBTDS) is expected to generate unprecedented volumes of high-cadence photometric observations across densely populated stellar fields. While these observations will significantly expand opportunities for exoplanet discovery through both transit and microlensing techniques, they also introduce challenges involving signal crowding, event classification, provenance tracking, and scientific reproducibility.

This work presents ASTRID (Automated Scientific Trust and Intent Routing Intelligence Director), a provenance-centered architectural framework developed within the Stellar Intelligence platform. Rather than treating classification as a single opaque prediction task, ASTRID organizes scientific reasoning through a structured four-stage validation pipeline: Observation, Evidence, Interpretation, and Uncertainty.

The framework introduces intent-based routing, auditable evidence chains, and immutable research journaling to ensure that each scientific conclusion remains traceable to its originating observations and supporting datasets. Simulated Roman-style transit and microlensing workflows demonstrate how the architecture can preserve transparency during high-throughput event analysis while reducing risks associated with metadata loss and non-explainable decision pathways.

This work proposes a reproducible foundation for future astronomical discovery systems where scientific trust, provenance, and interpretability are treated as first-class design requirements.

